they're no right or wrong ports.

the list of executors is defined in the miner config. and this is what the miner gossips to the validator once they connect. So the idea is this;

```
miner     <--- discovers executors via config  |             # see [executor_management] in config/miner.prod.toml
miner     ---- Keeps health heartbeat ---------> executor[N] # via executor's grpc_address

Validator ---- discovers via metagraph --------> miner       # Register nodes (we then filter down with valid commitments)
Validator ---- finds IP:PORT via commitments --> miner       # This is based on the advertised port. Needs to be internet accessible.
Validator <--- exchange List of executors ------ miner       # RPC call based on discovered IP:PORT
Validator ---- shares ssh details -------------> miner       # Pub key + id
miner     ---- ask executor to whitelist ssh --> executor    # executor manages the compute box
Validator ---- verifies via ssh ---------------> executor[N] # based on what the miner has gossip

Validator <--- ephemeral save of healthy Nodes |
Validator <--- set scores + weights            |
```

so the ports can be whatever you define in the config, the network discovers them as long they are correct and internet accessible.

- QUIC can often send application data in the very first flight compared to TCP which needs at least one round-trip before data.
- multiple HTTP/2 streams share a single TCP connection. If any TCP packet is lost, delivery of all streams stalls until that packet is retransmitted vs QUIC stream which is delivered independently. Loss on one stream only stalls that stream’s data, without blocking others. 
- QUIC connections are identified by connection IDs, not IP and port tuples, so an RPC client can change IPs so a client can maintain a connection even if its changes its ip.
- Better congestion control. 
- QUIC runs over UDP so NAT traversals if you need that stuff.

the way the categories and weight allocation work on the current scoring algorithm is this

0. Pre-step: each category has a fixed percentage that we want to incentivize based on the projected demand for what kind of inventory we need to have in basilica
1. firstly, miners are split into categories based on what gpu profiles we've validated for them on each epoch
2. then we split that category's allocation to as many miners, we share the pie
3. there's a small multiplier of the longevity of the  availability of the UID (244 was the first - or one of the first - UID that got validated as I saw)
4. on top of that the burn allocation is applied

this means that if you race solo in a less crowded category, you'll end up with bigger chunks of the pie, although the h100 pie was bigger.

next steps for the team

- we're investigating what works the best for the scoring incentives. we're not saying this game theory is the best. Feedback is welcome.

yes, the new score formula is as such

```
total_attestations = number of attempts we've perform to validate your hardware on the last 3hr
valid_attestations = number of successfull hardware validations (on the last 3hr)
gpu_count = number of gpus we've identified when we validated you
max_gpu_count = 8 (constant value)
score = (valid_attestations / total_attestations) * (gpu_count / max_gpu_count)
```

the greater the score, the bigger the allocation in the GPU category.

- `category_score = validation_ratio x gpu_count` # now the GPU count will be across all the machines they share (for each category)

- `total_category_score = SUM(validation_ratio_i x gpu_count_i) for all miners i in C` # each miner is racing locally against how populated each category is
- `miner_weight_in_category = (category_score / total_category_score) x category_weight_pool`

Final miner weight:
- `SUM(miner_weight_in_category)` # across all categories, the miners weight is a simple SUM of all their weighted score across the hardware they offer on different categories.
